<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-09">
  <title>Week 9</title>
  <subsection>
    <title>Monday</title>
    <p>
      This class featured a discussion of mapping spaces, what they're good for, and what we might 
      ask of them. Given its informal nature, I won't record notes here.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Wednesday</title>
    <p>
      Last week we introduced adjunctions and explored several examples: free <m>\dashv</m> forgetful
      adjunctions, the currying adjunction in <m>\mathsf{Set}</m>, and the discrete <m>\dashv</m>
      forgetful <m>\dashv</m> concrete adjunction for <m>\mathsf{Top}\to\mathsf{Set}</m>. Our goal
      this week is to pursue the topological currying adjunction: equipping the set of continuous maps
      <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m> with a topology so that product and mapping space form an adjoint pair.
    </p>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-motivation-mapping-spaces">
      <title>Motivation: topologies on function spaces</title>
      <p>
        For topological spaces <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>, the set <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m> of continuous
        maps from <m>X</m> to <m>Y</m> is just a set. Can we promote it to a topological space? And
        if so, which topology should we choose?
      </p>
      <p>
        Recall the currying adjunction in <m>\mathsf{Set}</m>: for a fixed set <m>S</m>, the functors
        <m>S\times(-)</m> and <m>(-)^S = \mathsf{Set}(S,-)</m> satisfy
        <md>
          \mathsf{Set}(S\times T, U) \cong \mathsf{Set}(T, U^S).
        </md>
        We would like an analogous statement in <m>\mathsf{Top}</m>: for a fixed space <m>X</m>, we
        want a topology on <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m> — call the resulting space <m>Y^X</m> — so that
        <md>
          \mathsf{Top}(X\times Z, Y) \cong \mathsf{Top}(Z, Y^X)
        </md>
        for all spaces <m>Y</m> and <m>Z</m>. When such a topology exists, we call it an
        <term>exponential topology</term> on <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Let us unpack what this adjunction would mean concretely. Reading from left to right, a
        continuous map <m>g\colon X\times Z\to Y</m> of two variables should curry to a continuous
        map <m>\hat{g}\colon Z\to Y^X</m>; that is, continuously parametrized families of continuous
        maps <m>X\to Y</m> should correspond to continuous maps into <m>Y^X</m>. Reading from right
        to left, a continuous map <m>F\colon Z\to Y^X</m> should uncurry to a continuous map
        <m>X\times Z\to Y</m>; the most basic instance of this (taking <m>Z = Y^X</m> and
        <m>F = \mathrm{id}</m>) produces the <term>evaluation map</term>
        <md>
          \mathrm{ev}\colon X\times Y^X \longrightarrow Y, \qquad (x,f)\longmapsto f(x),
        </md>
        which should be continuous.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-splitting-conjoining">
      <title>Splitting and conjoining topologies</title>
      <p>
        The discussion above suggests two properties a topology <m>\tau</m> on
        <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m> might have.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-splitting-conjoining">
        <title>Splitting and conjoining topologies</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> be topological spaces, and let <m>\tau</m> be a topology
            on <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\tau</m> is <term>splitting</term> :iff, for every space <m>Z</m>, the
                  continuity of <m>g\colon X\times Z\to Y</m> implies the continuity of the curried map
                  <m>\hat{g}\colon Z\to (\mathsf{Top}(X,Y),\tau)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\tau</m> is <term>conjoining</term> :iff, for every space <m>Z</m>, the
                  continuity of <m>\hat{g}\colon Z\to (\mathsf{Top}(X,Y),\tau)</m> implies the
                  continuity of the uncurried map <m>g\colon X\times Z\to Y</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
          <p>
            A topology that is both splitting and conjoining is an <term>exponential topology</term>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-conjoining-iff-eval">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A topology <m>\tau</m> on <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m> is conjoining if and only if
            the evaluation map <m>\mathrm{ev}\colon X\times (\mathsf{Top}(X,Y),\tau)\to Y</m>
            is continuous.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Suppose <m>\mathrm{ev}</m> is continuous. Given a continuous
            <m>\hat{g}\colon Z\to (\mathsf{Top}(X,Y),\tau)</m>, the uncurried map
            <m>g = \mathrm{ev}\circ(\mathrm{id}_X\times\hat{g})</m> is a composition of continuous
            maps, hence continuous.
          </p>
          <p>
            Conversely, suppose <m>\tau</m> is conjoining. The identity map
            <m>\mathrm{id}\colon (\mathsf{Top}(X,Y),\tau)\to (\mathsf{Top}(X,Y),\tau)</m>
            is continuous, so the uncurried map — which is precisely <m>\mathrm{ev}</m> — is continuous.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-splitting-coarser-conjoining">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Every splitting topology on <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m> is coarser than every conjoining
            topology.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Let <m>\tau</m> be splitting and <m>\tau'</m> be conjoining. Since
            <m>\tau'</m> is conjoining, the evaluation map
            <m>\mathrm{ev}\colon X\times(\mathsf{Top}(X,Y),\tau')\to Y</m> is continuous. Since
            <m>\tau</m> is splitting, the curried map
            <m>\mathrm{id}\colon (\mathsf{Top}(X,Y),\tau')\to (\mathsf{Top}(X,Y),\tau)</m>
            is continuous, which means <m>\tau\subseteq\tau'</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-exponential-unique">
        <title>Uniqueness of exponential topologies</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If an exponential topology on <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m> exists, then it is unique.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            An exponential topology is both splitting and conjoining, so by
            <xref ref="lem-splitting-coarser-conjoining" />, any two exponential topologies are each
            coarser than the other.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-compact-open-topology">
      <title>The compact-open topology</title>
      <p>
        We now define the compact-open topology and show it is always splitting. The key question —
        when is it also conjoining? — will be taken up on Friday.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-compact-open">
        <title>Compact-open topology</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> be topological spaces. For each compact subspace
            <m>K\subseteq X</m> and each open subset <m>U\subseteq Y</m>, define
            <md>
              [K,U] := \{f\in\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)\mid f(K)\subseteq U\}.
            </md>
            The sets <m>[K,U]</m> form a subbasis for a topology on <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m> called
            the <term>compact-open topology</term>. We write <m>Y^X</m> for <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m>
            equipped with this topology.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <remark>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The subbasis sets <m>[K,U]</m> form a <em>sub</em>basis, not generally a basis. Their
            finite intersections
            <md>
              [K_1,U_1]\cap\cdots\cap [K_n,U_n]
            </md>
            form a basis.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </remark>
      <example xml:id="eg-compact-open-discrete">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X=\{1,\ldots,r\}</m> with the discrete topology and let <m>Y</m> be any topological
            space. Then <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y) = Y^r</m> as a set. The compact subsets of <m>X</m> are
            all subsets (since <m>X</m> is finite), and the subbasis sets <m>[\{k\},U] =
            \{(y_1,\ldots,y_r)\mid y_k\in U\}</m> generate the product topology on <m>Y^r</m>. So in
            this case the compact-open topology agrees with the (finite) product topology.
          </p>
          <p>
            This observation will guide us toward the correct definition of the product topology for
            arbitrary (possibly infinite) families of spaces.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-compact-open-splitting">
        <title>The compact-open topology is splitting</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For any spaces <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>, the compact-open topology on
            <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m> is splitting.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Let <m>Z</m> be any space and suppose <m>g\colon X\times Z\to Y</m> is continuous. We need
            to show that the curried map <m>\hat{g}\colon Z\to Y^X</m> is continuous. It suffices to
            show that <m>\hat{g}^{-1}([K,U])</m> is open in <m>Z</m> for each compact
            <m>K\subseteq X</m> and open <m>U\subseteq Y</m>. Now,
            <m>\hat{g}^{-1}([K,U]) = \{z\in Z\mid g(K,z)\subseteq U\}</m>. Since <m>g</m> is
            continuous, <m>g^{-1}(U)</m> is open in <m>X\times Z</m> and contains <m>K\times\{z\}</m>.
            By the Tube Lemma, there are open sets <m>K\subseteq V</m> and <m>z\in W</m> with
            <m>K\times\{z\}\subseteq V\times W\subseteq g^{-1}(U)</m>. Therefore
            <m>z\in W\subseteq \hat{g}^{-1}([K,U])</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-product-via-compact-open">
      <title>The product topology via mapping spaces</title>
      <p>
        So far in this course, we have only defined products of <em>finitely many</em> topological
        spaces: given spaces <m>X_1,\ldots,X_n</m>, the product <m>X_1\times\cdots\times X_n</m>
        carries the topology generated by products of open sets <m>U_1\times\cdots\times U_n</m>. The
        compact-open topology gives us a conceptual way to extend this definition to arbitrary (possibly
        infinite) products.
      </p>
      <p>
        The key observation is <xref ref="eg-compact-open-discrete" />: when <m>A</m> is a finite
        discrete space, the compact-open topology on <m>Y^A = \mathsf{Top}(A,Y)</m> recovers the
        product topology on the finite product <m>Y^{|A|}</m>. But the definition of the compact-open
        topology makes perfect sense when <m>A</m> is an <em>infinite</em> discrete set — and this
        tells us what the right topology on an infinite product should be.
      </p>
      <p>
        Let <m>A</m> be any set, equipped with the discrete topology. Since every function out of a
        discrete space is continuous, we have <m>\mathsf{Top}(A,Y) = Y^A</m> as sets. The compact-open
        subbasis sets are <m>[K,U]</m> for <m>K\subseteq A</m> compact and <m>U\subseteq Y</m> open.
        Since <m>A</m> is discrete, its compact subsets are precisely its <em>finite</em> subsets. The
        subbasis set <m>[\{\alpha\},U]</m> for a single element <m>\alpha\in A</m> is
        <md>
          [\{\alpha\},U] = \{f\in Y^A\mid f(\alpha)\in U\} = \mathrm{pr}_\alpha^{-1}(U),
        </md>
        where <m>\mathrm{pr}_\alpha\colon Y^A\to Y</m> is projection onto the <m>\alpha</m>-th
        coordinate. In other words, the compact-open topology on <m>Y^A</m> is the coarsest topology
        making every projection continuous. We promote this observation to a definition.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-product-topology">
        <title>Product topology</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>\{Y_\alpha\}_{\alpha\in A}</m> be a family of topological spaces. The
            <term>product topology</term> on the set <m>\prod_{\alpha\in A}Y_\alpha</m> is the
            coarsest topology for which every projection map
            <md>
              \mathrm{pr}_\alpha\colon \prod_{\beta\in A}Y_\beta\longrightarrow Y_\alpha, \qquad
              (y_\beta)_{\beta\in A}\longmapsto y_\alpha,
            </md>
            is continuous.
          </p>
          <p>
            Equivalently, the product topology has subbasis
            <md>
              \bigl\{\mathrm{pr}_\alpha^{-1}(U)\mid \alpha\in A,\;U\subseteq Y_\alpha\text{ open}\bigr\}.
            </md>
            A basis consists of all finite intersections of these subbasis sets, <ie />, sets of the form
            <md>
              \mathrm{pr}_{\alpha_1}^{-1}(U_1)\cap\cdots\cap\mathrm{pr}_{\alpha_n}^{-1}(U_n)
            </md>
            where <m>\alpha_1,\ldots,\alpha_n\in A</m> and each <m>U_i\subseteq Y_{\alpha_i}</m> is
            open.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <remark>
        <statement>
          <p>
            When <m>Y_\alpha = Y</m> for all <m>\alpha</m>, the product <m>\prod_\alpha Y</m> is
            the set <m>Y^A</m> of functions <m>A\to Y</m>. If <m>A</m> carries the discrete topology,
            this is <m>\mathsf{Top}(A,Y)</m>, and the product topology is exactly the compact-open
            topology, as argued above. For a general (non-discrete) space <m>X</m>, the product
            topology on <m>Y^X</m> has subbasis sets <m>[\{x\},U] = \mathrm{pr}_x^{-1}(U)</m>
            indexed by <em>singletons</em>, while the compact-open topology allows arbitrary compact
            <m>K</m>. Since singletons are compact, the compact-open topology is always finer than the
            product topology.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </remark>
      <p>
        As always, we should ask: what is the universal property? The product topology is designed
        exactly so that continuous maps <em>into</em> a product are determined by their coordinates.
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-product-universal-property">
        <title>Universal property of products</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>\{Y_\alpha\}_{\alpha\in A}</m> be a family of topological spaces. For any
            topological space <m>Z</m>, a map
            <md>
              f\colon Z\longrightarrow \prod_{\alpha\in A}Y_\alpha
            </md>
            is continuous if and only if <m>\mathrm{pr}_\alpha\circ f\colon Z\to Y_\alpha</m> is
            continuous for every <m>\alpha\in A</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            In other words, there is a bijection of sets
            <md>
              \mathsf{Top}\!\left(Z,\,\prod_{\alpha\in A}Y_\alpha\right) \xrightarrow{\;\cong\;}
              \prod_{\alpha\in A}\mathsf{Top}(Z,Y_\alpha), \qquad f\longmapsto
              (\mathrm{pr}_\alpha\circ f)_{\alpha\in A},
            </md>
            natural in <m>Z</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            The "only if" direction is immediate: if <m>f</m> is continuous, then
            <m>\mathrm{pr}_\alpha\circ f</m> is a composition of continuous maps, hence continuous.
          </p>
          <p>
            For the "if" direction, suppose <m>\mathrm{pr}_\alpha\circ f</m> is continuous for every
            <m>\alpha</m>. To show <m>f</m> is continuous, it suffices to check preimages of subbasis
            sets. For each subbasis set <m>\mathrm{pr}_\alpha^{-1}(U)</m> in the product, we have
            <md>
              f^{-1}\bigl(\mathrm{pr}_\alpha^{-1}(U)\bigr)
              = (\mathrm{pr}_\alpha\circ f)^{-1}(U),
            </md>
            which is open in <m>Z</m> by the assumed continuity of
            <m>\mathrm{pr}_\alpha\circ f</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>
      <remark>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The product topology is the <em>unique</em> topology on <m>\prod_\alpha Y_\alpha</m>
            satisfying this universal property. Indeed, if <m>\tau</m> is any topology making the
            projections continuous and satisfying the universal property, then the identity map
            <m>\mathrm{id}\colon(\prod_\alpha Y_\alpha,\tau_{\mathrm{prod}})\to(\prod_\alpha
            Y_\alpha,\tau)</m> is continuous (since each projection from the product topology is
            continuous), and vice versa.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </remark>
      <p>
        We record an important special case connecting back to our discussion of mapping spaces.
      </p>
      <corollary xml:id="cor-maps-into-product">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>A</m> be a set (with discrete topology) and <m>Y</m> a topological space. For
            any space <m>Z</m>, there is a natural bijection
            <md>
              \mathsf{Top}(Z,Y^A)\xrightarrow{\;\cong\;}\mathsf{Top}(Z,Y)^A,
            </md>
            where <m>Y^A = \prod_{\alpha\in A}Y</m> carries the product topology. That is, a continuous
            map from <m>Z</m> into <m>Y^A</m> is the same thing as an <m>A</m>-indexed family of
            continuous maps <m>Z\to Y</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </corollary>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-metrics-function-spaces">
      <title>Metrics on function spaces</title>
      <p>
        When the target space <m>(Y,d)</m> is a metric space, one can define several natural topologies
        on the set <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m> via metrics or pseudometrics. For a subset
        <m>A\subseteq X</m>, a map <m>f\colon X\to Y</m>, and <m>\varepsilon\gt 0</m>, write
        <md>
          \mathrm{B}_\varepsilon^A(f) := \{g\in\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)\mid \sup_{x\in A}d(f(x),g(x))\lt\varepsilon\}
        </md>
        for the <m>\varepsilon</m>-ball about <m>f</m> measured on <m>A</m>. Varying <m>A</m> yields
        three topologies on <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Pointwise convergence.</term> Take <m>A = \{x\}</m> for each <m>x\in X</m>. The
              resulting topology <m>\tau_{\mathrm{pw}}</m> on <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m> coincides with
              the subspace topology from the product <m>Y^X = \prod_{x\in X}Y</m>. A sequence
              <m>(f_n)</m> converges to <m>f</m> in this topology if and only if <m>f_n(x)\to f(x)</m>
              for each <m>x\in X</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Compact convergence.</term> Take <m>A = K</m> for each compact <m>K\subseteq X</m>.
              The resulting topology <m>\tau_{\mathrm{cpt}}</m> is coarser than the uniform topology
              and finer than the pointwise topology. A sequence <m>(f_n)</m> converges to <m>f</m> if
              and only if <m>(f_n|_K)</m> converges uniformly to <m>f|_K</m> for every compact
              <m>K\subseteq X</m>. When <m>Y</m> is a metric space, the compact convergence topology on
              <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m> agrees with the compact-open topology.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Uniform convergence.</term> Take <m>A = X</m>. When <m>X</m> is compact, this
              agrees with the compact convergence topology (since <m>X</m> itself is compact). In
              general, the uniform topology is finer: it requires convergence to be uniform over all of
              <m>X</m> simultaneously. When <m>X</m> is compact, the <term>sup metric</term>
              <m>d_\infty(f,g) := \sup_{x\in X}d(f(x),g(x))</m> defines the topology, and
              <m>(\mathsf{Top}(X,Y),d_\infty)</m> is a metric space.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      <p>
        Summarizing: there is a chain of inclusions among topologies on <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m>,
        <md>
          \tau_{\mathrm{pw}}\subseteq\tau_{\mathrm{cpt}}\subseteq\tau_{\mathrm{unif}},
        </md>
        and when <m>X</m> is compact, the latter two coincide. We omit the (straightforward but
        somewhat technical) proofs that the compact convergence and compact-open topologies agree; see
        Section 11.5 of the graduate notes for details. An important consequence of this agreement is
        that a classical theorem — the uniform limit of continuous functions is continuous — can be
        reinterpreted as saying that <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m> is a closed subspace of the space of
        all maps <m>X\to Y</m> in the compact convergence topology.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Friday</title>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-evaluation-continuous">
      <title>Continuity of evaluation and the exponential adjunction</title>
      <p>
        On Wednesday we saw that the compact-open topology is always splitting. The question remains:
        when is it conjoining? By <xref ref="lem-conjoining-iff-eval" />, this is equivalent to asking
        when the evaluation map <m>\mathrm{ev}\colon X\times Y^X\to Y</m> is continuous. The answer
        involves a familiar condition on <m>X</m>.
      </p>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-eval-continuous-lc">
        <title>Continuity of the evaluation map</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> be topological spaces. If <m>X</m> is locally compact, then the
            evaluation map
            <md>
              \mathrm{ev}\colon X\times Y^X \longrightarrow Y, \qquad (x,f)\longmapsto f(x),
            </md>
            is continuous, where <m>Y^X = \mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m> carries the compact-open topology.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Let <m>U\subseteq Y</m> be open. We must show the preimage
            <m>\mathrm{ev}^{-1}(U)\subseteq X\times Y^X</m> is open. Let
            <m>(x,f)\in\mathrm{ev}^{-1}(U)</m>, so <m>f(x)\in U</m>. Since <m>f</m> is continuous,
            <m>f^{-1}(U)</m> is an open neighborhood of <m>x</m> in <m>X</m>. Since <m>X</m> is locally
            compact, there is a compact subspace <m>K\subseteq X</m> with
            <md>
              x\in\mathrm{Int}(K)\subseteq K\subseteq f^{-1}(U).
            </md>
            Then <m>f(K)\subseteq U</m>, so <m>f\in [K,U]</m>. The set
            <m>\mathrm{Int}(K)\times [K,U]</m> is an open neighborhood of <m>(x,f)</m> in
            <m>X\times Y^X</m>. For any <m>(x',f')</m> in this neighborhood, we have
            <m>x'\in\mathrm{Int}(K)\subseteq K</m> and <m>f'(K)\subseteq U</m>, so
            <m>f'(x')\in U</m>, confirming
            <m>\mathrm{Int}(K)\times [K,U]\subseteq\mathrm{ev}^{-1}(U)</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-compact-open-exponential">
        <title>The exponential adjunction for locally compact spaces</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> be a locally compact topological space and let <m>Y</m> be any topological
            space. Then the compact-open topology on <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m> is exponential. That
            is, for every space <m>Z</m>, currying and uncurrying define inverse bijections
            <md>
              \mathsf{Top}(X\times Z, Y) \cong \mathsf{Top}(Z, Y^X)
            </md>
            that are natural in <m>Y</m> and <m>Z</m>. In the language of adjunctions, this says
            <md>
              X\times(-)\;\dashv\;(-)^X\colon\mathsf{Top}\longrightarrow\mathsf{Top}.
            </md>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            By <xref ref="thm-compact-open-splitting" />, the compact-open topology is splitting, and
            by <xref ref="lem-eval-continuous-lc" /> and <xref ref="lem-conjoining-iff-eval" />, it is
            conjoining when <m>X</m> is locally compact.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>
      <remark>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The unit of the adjunction <m>X\times(-)\dashv(-)^X</m> is the <term>coevaluation</term>
            map
            <md>
              \mathrm{coev}\colon Z\longrightarrow (Y^X)^Z,\qquad z\longmapsto (f\mapsto f(z))?
            </md>
            Wait — that doesn't quite parse! In fact, the unit at <m>Z</m> is a map
            <m>\eta_Z\colon Z\to (X\times Z)^X</m> given by <m>\eta_Z(z) = (x\mapsto (x,z))</m>. The
            counit is the evaluation map <m>\varepsilon_Y\colon X\times Y^X\to Y</m>. Verify the
            triangle identities as an exercise!
          </p>
        </statement>
      </remark>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-currying-applications">
      <title>Applications of the exponential adjunction</title>
      <p>
        The exponential adjunction has many pleasant consequences. We record several here.
      </p>
      <corollary xml:id="cor-composition-continuous">
        <title>Continuity of composition</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m>, <m>Y</m>, and <m>Z</m> be topological spaces with <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>
            locally compact. Then the composition map
            <md>
              \circ\colon Y^X\times Z^Y\longrightarrow Z^X, \qquad (f,g)\longmapsto g\circ f,
            </md>
            is continuous.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            The uncurrying of the composition map is the continuous map
            <md>
              X\times Y^X\times Z^Y \xrightarrow{\;\mathrm{ev}\times\mathrm{id}\;} Y\times Z^Y
              \xrightarrow{\;\mathrm{ev}\;} Z, \qquad (x,f,g)\longmapsto g(f(x)).
            </md>
            Both evaluation maps are continuous (since <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> are locally compact), as
            are products and compositions of continuous maps.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </corollary>
      <corollary xml:id="cor-exponential-identity">
        <title>Exponential law for mapping spaces</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> and <m>Z</m> be locally compact and let <m>Y</m> be any space. The currying
            bijection
            <md>
              Y^{X\times Z}\xrightarrow{\;\cong\;} (Y^X)^Z
            </md>
            is a homeomorphism. This categorifies the identity <m>y^{xz}=(y^x)^z</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            This is an exercise. (Hint: one can give a clean proof using the fact that both sides
            represent the same functor, appealing to the Yoneda lemma.)
          </p>
        </proof>
      </corollary>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-limitations">
      <title>Limitations and the role of local compactness</title>
      <p>
        It is natural to ask how essential the hypothesis of local compactness is. The short answer: very.
      </p>
      <p>
        The category <m>\mathsf{Top}</m> is <em>not</em> Cartesian closed: there is no way to
        functorially equip <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m> with a topology making the product-hom adjunction
        work for all spaces <m>X</m>. Locally compact Hausdorff spaces are well-behaved in this
        respect, but problems arise even for simple spaces.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="eg-R-infty-not-lc">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider the colimit of the diagram
            <md>
              \mathbb{R}\hookrightarrow\mathbb{R}^2\hookrightarrow\mathbb{R}^3\hookrightarrow\cdots
            </md>
            in <m>\mathsf{Top}</m>. The resulting space <m>\mathbb{R}^\infty</m> is not locally compact,
            so the exponential adjunction may fail for mapping spaces with domain
            <m>\mathbb{R}^\infty</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        One remedy is to restrict attention to a <term>convenient category</term> of topological
        spaces — one that is Cartesian closed and contains all the spaces we care about. The category
        of <term>compactly generated weakly Hausdorff</term> (CGWH) spaces is the standard choice. A
        topological space <m>X</m> is <term>compactly generated</term> if <m>A\subseteq X</m> is open
        whenever <m>A\cap K</m> is open in <m>K</m> for every compact <m>K\subseteq X</m>. Locally
        compact spaces are compactly generated, and the CGWH category has enough structure to support
        mapping spaces, quotients, and all the constructions we need for algebraic topology.
      </p>
      <p>
        We will not develop the theory of CGWH spaces in this course, but it is good to be aware that
        the exponential adjunction can be rescued by working in an appropriate subcategory. In
        practice, all the spaces we encounter (manifolds, CW complexes, metric spaces, <etc />) are
        locally compact Hausdorff, and the compact-open topology works beautifully for them.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-stone-cech-construction">
      <title>Application: Stone-Čech compactification via mapping spaces</title>
      <p>
        Recall from <xref ref="subsubsec-stone-cech" /> that for any topological space <m>X</m>, the
        Stone-Čech compactification <m>\beta X</m> is a compact Hausdorff space equipped with a
        continuous map <m>\eta_X\colon X\to\beta X</m> such that every continuous map from <m>X</m>
        to a compact Hausdorff space <m>Y</m> extends uniquely across <m>\eta_X</m>. With the
        compact-open topology in hand, we can at least <em>describe</em> how one constructs
        <m>\beta X</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Consider the unit interval <m>[0,1]</m>, which is compact Hausdorff. For any completely
        regular space <m>X</m>, the evaluation map
        <md>
          X\longrightarrow [0,1]^{\mathsf{Top}(X,[0,1])}, \qquad x\longmapsto (\mathrm{ev}_x\colon
          f\mapsto f(x)),
        </md>
        is an embedding. The closure of the image is a compact Hausdorff space, and this is
        <m>\beta X</m>.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>

  </subsection>

</section>
